The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, July 04, 2003  Business Briefs Washington, July 3: Indian financial  expert Raghuram Rajan has been named as the International  Monetary Funds new chief economist. IMF managing director  Horst Kohler has proposed Rajans name to the prestigious  and high visibility post with the official title of economic  counsellor and director of the IMFs research department.  Calcutta, July 3: The management of  SSI Ltd today decided to raise up to $ 50 million (Rs 230  crore) through issue of shares or other instruments that  could be converted into shares in India and abroad. The  amount will be used to expand SSIs software services business  through acquisitions. New Delhi, July 3: FMCG major Dabur  India has decided to delist its shares from eight stock  exchanges in the country, including Delhi, on account of  insignificant trading on these exchanges. At present, Dabur  is listed on 10 stock exchanges and over 95 per cent of  the volumes are traded on NSE and BSE alone.  New York, July 3: MCI, the rebaptised  WorldCom seeking to emerge from bankruptcy, has offered  an extra $ 250 million to holders of company stock and bonds  to settle fraud charges, bringing the total to a record  $ 750 million. New Delhi, July 3: NYSE-listed Perot  Systems will acquire Chennai-based Vision, a healthcare  claims processing company, for an aggregate value of $ 10  million.
